76561198353573538,Recommended,274520,33704509,Posted: 21 July,all,derpykat5,"This is one of the best survival games I have ever seen. in the steam forums I compared it to Dont Starve. however I feel that doesn't come close to describing it fully. this is practically the only game on steam I have seen that has an engaging and open story. the story itself is interactable. your choices directly and indirectly affect the story and outcomes. despite the emphasis on story, Darkwood is a very solid game even ignoring the story. you run around a randomly generated map collecting resources like wood and nails. you use these resources to fortify your hideout. during the night, you have to retreat to your hideout, turn on your generator and retreat to a back fortified room to cower in the corner until morning. this  is the genre of survival that throws you into the madness with no handholding apart from an optional prolouge that, while also serves as an introduction to the controls, delivers a lot of story. the entire game is very eerie and can be downright terrifying sometimes. it also obeys the laws of physics. meaning you cant just build what you want or sprint forever, but also, there is a unique ""cone of vision"" that complicates things. you can only see movement and enemies when they are in your cone of vision. other things, like the landscape and structures, stay visible no matter what you are looking at, so you are not completely lost. the ""voices"" mainly consist of floating text, however this allows you to pinpoint somethings location without seeing it, like you could IRL. NPCs and enemies behave realistically, for instance dogs turn tail and run once their health drops below a certain point. savages cant see you if you are behind them. crafting requires a lot of work. things break easily, and so on. this game was originally polish (I think) or set somewhere in poland, although the game is available in complete perfect english there are still a few polish things, like a polish cigar box, and a polish newspaper. these items have little to no effect on the game though, and are just to reinforce that unfamiliar aspect. the game is also leaving early access august 17, so thats another thing to look forward to.one word of warning: Darkwood is just that; dark. you have the option to kill almost every quest giver to avoid completing their quest. this can and does impact the story in various ways. blood, gore, and swearing are abound. PG13.in short, yes, get this game, but not yet. wait for it to hit release as every major update in the past did not come with save compatibility. hopefully this changes after release, as the future updates wont have such drastic changes that caused the save incompatibility."
