,Recommended,274520,21061865,"Posted: 8 February, 2016",all,AschTheConjurer,"Darkwood is an Early Access title, this review is subject to change. Date and Version at time ofwritingediting: December 18th -- Alpha 8.1TL;DR: One of only two Early Access games I didn't feel cheated out of my money on, and in fact highly recommend. Please fund these guys.Darkwood, from The Acid Wizards, is based on atmosphere and tension. Rather than resorting to jump-scares it relies on psychological horror andorganicscares in the sandbox. It's also a game whose mechanics are kinda hard to describe or summarize without spoiling. But I'll try:This top-down title achieves 'scariness' partly due to great artistic style and sound design, but mechanically it's because of your line-of-sight - the way that light and your LOS interact to affect your ability to see in the dark is reminiscent of the foreboding feeling most people got from Silent Hill 2's fog.Speaking of darkness, Night is probably the most important mechanic other than light and sight so far. At the end of each day one must survive through the night. Hide in a corner behind a wardrobe you dragged over and barely scrape by - or take the fight to those who would hunt you, and enjoy the spoils of war.[Updated Note:]Changes to Nighttime have introduced an unkillable enemy that forces you to stay indoors during the dark hours. This mechanic is highly controversial among the early-access community.Combat is rather precise and unforgiving like the Souls games or CRAWL, but in sandbox fashion can mostly be avoided by hiding well or fleeing. Different melee weapons provide different tactics: you'll likely find your favorite bashing tool and religiously stick with it. Firearms are an expensive resource, but will give those struggling with meleefar morethan just an edge if they can source themselves some ammunition.By day, you explore the world for crafting items and NPCs using landmarks automatically marked on your map once close enough. Some landmarks and areas have function or loot, others are solely for navigation. The shape of the world and the location of, and loot in, each setpiece changes each new game (with few exceptions). Combined with the permadeath difficulty, a very satisfying rogue-like experience is available.When story isn't extracted in a Dark-Soulsian way (by the player inferring things from the environment), it comes from artistic cinematics, or the flavourful NPCs. While they communicate in small walls of text, they're aided by anunsettlinglyanimated portrait. This is shared with the greater world, where some lootable bodies, hostile flooring, items needed for XP, and even some idle enemies have strange and twitchy, but creepily organic animations.[Updated Note:] The Acid Wizards have doubled-down on their artstyle and worldbuilding with it. Players who find their way to Chapter 2 will be richly rewarded with some of the most ♥♥♥♥ed-up-cool♥♥♥♥♥♥I've ever seen depicted in a videogame. H.R. Giger ain't got♥♥♥♥♥♥on these Polish fellows.At current the game's second chapter ends rather abruptly, leaving the player to free-roam the second chapter's map, but this is somewhat made up for by the number of places one can explore, and the irregular updates that either provide a shovel of new content or reworked game mechanics, requiring players to find more efficient playstyles under new rules.Summary:Darkwood might be an incomplete game with [literally:] one or two flaws, but I believe the art, atmosphere, gameplay, and effort are more than worth anyone's time. I'd put it on-par with a few of Steam's other indies like Nuclear Throne, or CRAWL, in that playing Darkwood is doing yourself a service."
76561197970800104,Recommended,274520,28437892,"Posted: 17 December, 2016",all,CAL9000,"Darkwood is an intense survival horror game set in a mysterious forest. The gameplay is viewed from a top-down perspective and blends combat, exploration, story and survival mechanics in a satisfying way. The prologue is deliciously disturbing and sets the tone of things to come: you start each day in your hideout and must venture out to collect supplies to safeguard yourself and your hideout. As you progress, you'll encounter numerous weird allies and enemies. There's some crafting elements - such as the ability to construct torches, weapons and bandages - and RPG additions - like the ability to inject odd mushrooms which give you various abilities/weaknesses.The unique gameplay mechanism comes in the form of the view cone wherein your character can only see things they are looking at directly. This creates alot of tension and many interesting gameplay scenarios: for instance, you may hear the snap of a twig or the bark of a demon dog as you explore the forest which may force you to look around, bolt away or tread more carefully. The game rewards careful planning and punishes wrecklessness. If you run mindlessly through the forest without checking to see what's around you you'll likely stumble into a beartrap or some poisoned mushrooms; if you take your time and play cautiously you will be able to progress to new regions and advance the story.The combat is nicely balanced and reminiscent of classic survival horror games: you don't feel overpowered but you can muster just enough equipment to defend yourself if you try. The game permits you to choose from 1 of 3 difficulties: the easiest difficulty gives you infinite lives and the option to collect some dropped equipment on death; the hardest difficulty - and by far the most thrilling - gives you just 1 life and forces you to play very carefully and cautiously. The game becomes even more terrifying by night as you must get back to your hideout and survive until morning. Many of the games best scares come at this point as numerous creatures try to break into your house and various strange events occur.The lighting/shadow effects are wonderful - especially considering the game is mostly in 2D - and the muted colour scheme and odd enemy/ally design combine to create an unnerving atmosphere. The sound design is incredibly atmospheric: the menu music captures the tone of the game perfectly and the dynamic soundtrack does a good job of setting the mood as the time and setting change. The 'Time Freeze' music is particularly wonderful and the sound effects are suitably strange and eerie throughout.So far I've played around 35 hours and explored 2/3 regions of the forest: I feel the game is already satisfying and worthy of its price tag based on the current content and my enjoyment thus far. My only minor complaints are some of the UI elements could be better explained - for instance it took me a little while to understand that many items in the world had their own progress/health bar - and it would be nice to be able to repair some of your damaged structures.The game is still in development however and I expect things will only get better as the Acid Wizard team push towards release.I would highly recommend this game to fans of 'weird' survival horrors like Silent Hill and Lone Survivor but if you're a fan of recent atmospheric survival games like The Long Dark you may find lots to enjoy here also."
