76561198031355289,Recommended,274520,34590794,Posted: 29 August,all,gruber_meister,"An atmospheric, jarring, and sonically stunning piece for a sphere of gaming (indie developers) that has seen a plethora of bad outcomes, Darkwood offers players a small chance at survival... if you're worthy.My first time playing this game I sat at my computer for a good 5 hours just trying to survive, I found some corpses with wooden planks and nails, made a nail-board, and pushed a wardrobe in front of the gaping hole in my safe-house in an effort to keep the baddies out. night came, and with it a sense of overwhelming isolation that left me hoping, pleading, praying for dawn to come. I was hooked. The nights got worse, however, as more and more terrifying creatures came knocking (or bursting into) the safehouse, giving only the slight, horrifyingly distinct screech of a wardrobe sliding across a wooden floor as a warning.By day, you will scavenge and craft your way to slightly stronger levels of self-defense and safehouse-reinforcement, but by night, all bets are off as the things that literally go bump in the night will try to claw their way not only into your haven, but also into your sanity.Tips:1. Buy a watch and lantern if you can't find them. you'll thank me later, when you're out and dont know how long you have left until nightfall, or need to fight when the lights go out because you forgot to fuel up the generator.2. USE YOUR GAINED REPUTATION. reputation is the currency of the woods, and each dawn you get an allotment to spend at the trader who visits your house. But the Wolf does not grant you more reputation, you must trade him for it... Choose your relinquished items wisely. A couple bottles of alcohol and a tank of gas might be worth it in the short term for a toolbox to upgrade your workbench, but you might also find that monsters have a great advantage in the dark, night vision, while you need torches and adequately fueled generators to see them and fight back. Which reminds me, TURN OFF THE GENERATOR IN THE DAYTIME... I've forgotten more than once.3. If you don't have to fight, don't fight. Things in this game are FAR more mobile than you, and will exploit that advantage at every possible opportunity. plus your weapons have durability, which will deplete with each swing.4. Read. This is a psychological horror, and has quite a cast of characters that become important, which means that it's vital to read what they have to say in order to progress and get the story elements.5. Learn to value the fine cloth. (I think that's what it's called) It's the item that allows you to expand your inventory space or hotbar, and it's amazing. You'll find tons of items, and it gets dangerous when you have to make a couple trips to get a bunch of nice things back to your homebase and into your workbench, which doubles as a storage cabinet.6. Listen intently to your surroundings. This game makes impressive use of sound as an immersion factor: twigs snap as you explore the woods, enemies will sometimes alert you to their presence with their noisy (and sometimes disturbingly nonsensical) behavior, and it is much better to rely on your sense of hearing than your sense of sight when the sun goes down. But keep the lights on in the house, anyway. It'll save you a huge headache.This game is great, and serves as a reminder to all indie developers of what can be achieved when you put in the work. I had the game since alpha, and never saw the devs give up on making the game better. Well done, Acid Wizards, well done."
