76561198144800785,Recommended,274520,29065844,Posted: 6 January,all,korben dallas,"This game is utterly fantastic, a true labor of love. Yes, it has been in development a long time, but progress is constant, and even a couple years ago this game was the type and quality you could replay over and over. It's that good. And it has only gotten better.It is, at its core, a survival and scavenging game. During the day, you leave the relative safety of your hideout to explore and scavenge the ruins of the world that is Darkwood. You collect crafting materials, and ferry them back to your hideout in an attempt to improve your situation. Do you want to use the wood you collected to board up those windows, rebuild that door, upgrade your workbench, or craft a new weapon? These choices have weight and affect your very survival.Of course, there are plenty of animals and ridiculously scary creatures to contend with as you do this, especially as you progress to increasingly difficult areas. The combat is tricky to get the hang of at first. Once you do, it's a very intense, yet rewarding system. It's not a kill, kill, kill type of game; each fight is a battle, and sometimes running your♥♥♥♥♥off is the only way to save yourself. There tends to be a desperate feel to it that can really get your heart going. For a game to draw the player in like that is quite a feat in its own right.Then nighttime comes. This is when you really have to hunker down, this is what you were preparing for during the day. This is the time when the violent creatures of Darkwood come to you looking for food, and they only have a taste for flesh.You fortify yourself in your hideout in one way or another, whether your broad strategy is to hide in a corner, patrol with weapons at the ready, or anything in between. You can craft and set traps, from something as simple as smashing a bottle on the ground to create a patch of broken glass, to working metal to create bear traps. You can stalk around in the dark (and it is DARK!) or utilize one of the many methods of creating light, such as using the generator (each hideout has one, but requires fuel to run it), crafting a torch or lamp, or dropping a (very valuable) flare. Again, each of these requiring resources. The game is filled with choices that may help you now, but leave you scraping tomorrow.I jumped right into talking about gameplay, because it's one of the many things that shines about this game. But it's really the atmosphere that gets the player into the characters shoes, makes you feel the intensity of it. They have achieved a very right combination of visuals, music, and creepy storylines to flesh out the Darkwood universe. And it is a creeeeepy place.In the end, after playing this game for countless hours (much of it offline), the only thing I really need from it is another difficulty level. Don't get me wrong, this game is difficult. It has a definite learning curve that can be punishing to new players. However, the game is so good that it's worth playing A LOT, and veteran status is bound to happen eventually. With the care and attention the devs give the game, I could see it being added down the line, closer to release. And still being in EA, anything is possible!PROS:-Atmosphere is phenomenally creepy-Intense, high stakes combat-Great scavenging and crafting system-Procedurally generated maps enhance replayability-A unique RPG-like skill system that forces a negative perk for every two positive-Day/Night system that pressures you to scavenge for supplies during the day, and make sure you're in shelter and fortified for the night-Multiple difficulties (unlimited lives, limited lives, permadeath)-Developers that are involved with the community and truly care about their gameCONS:-Perhaps not the best game for the overly-casual gamer, as there is a decent learning curve-Once the learning curve is finally overcome, the game eventually becomes too easy; as it stands in EA, veterans are clamoring for a more difficult setting than even permadeathAs Darkwood nears completion, it is better than ever. One of the best games I've ever played, let alone one of the best indy games. Darkwood is a world I will be returning to again and again."
