76561198040590657,Recommended,274520,26819577,"Posted: 23 November, 2016",all,this nick is a lie,"Hidden gem, i still hope it will get more recognition so devs will have more money to finish the game faster."
,Recommended,274520,34357010,Posted: 19 August,all,malaisling,"An incredible gaming experience.Fantastic art, solid animation, amazing graphical effects, lots of content, a simple but satisfying combat system, great thrilling atmosphere with no jumpscares, gorgeous world and lore design. All around, masterpiece game.There is not much to complement in depth since it all simply is just really well done and very fun to play. However it should be noted that the game is more linear then it sounds. The world is decently randomized, and involves lots of free roam exploration, however the game still progresses based on quests and objectives. There is an overarching story which the protagonist is following, it isn't just an open survival experience.The biggest problem a player may have with the gameplay, is that it involves a lot of scavenging and travelling. Players run around each map, looking for resources and bringing them back to their hideout, fighting enemies whenever they appear or run into them. At night they stay in their hideout and wait for dawn. A significant amount of the gameplay is travelling between locations, so players that prefer fast paced gameplay will likely not be able to stand this much.Most of the downsides of the game itself are negligible but still note worthy.Players can only move at a decent pace by running, and running drains from the small stamina gauge players have. It is thus common to have to briefly stop or slow to a walk to regain stamina; which can be very tedious since the game involves a decent amount of travelling.The combat, while being very fun, has some rough edges. The game does que the players offensive moves, so if players try to attack and get interrupted; they will auto-attack when they can next. Which is blatantly annoying and can lead to unnecessary harm recieved. There is also the problem of some enemies being more offensive then the player can respond to, so if the player gets flustered or ambushed they can get stun-locked because it requires so much precision to properly respond and counter the enemy that it isn't always possible when under pressure. Certain weapons also consume ridiculous amounts of stamina to use, which makes it borderline impossible to fight more aggressive enemies which players need to be able to interrupt. Meaning at certain stages of the game, certain weapons become useless. Certain enemies are blatantly faster then the player offencively, and require dodging and spacing to fight, however because the player isn't agile getting hit a few times is almost mandatory unless the player fights with exact precision at all times. It is even worse since players have to charge most of their attacks, and sometimes they will pause before attacking if they are getting hit.The game also likes punishing players with free damage because they stepped on one of the numerous ground traps and hazards in the game. Which would be fine if a lot of them weren't difficult to see in general, especially when the mixed lighting and limited visibility range are factored in.During chapter transition periods of the game players also lose all the items they had in their previous base since they move to a brand new one in a seperate map. Only the items they brought with them are kept, so if players do not know this ahead of time they lose the opportunity to transfer more precious items over. The same can be said for exploring, if players do not know what mission advances the chapter they may end up doing it, getting advanced forward, and missing the chance to explore more in the original map.The random generation of the world is also not completely random. The world is pretty random, but every map has the same locations and points of interest inside it. They are just placed in different areas of that map and have slightly different layouts. So players will find that if they replay the game they will see the same locations again, which can harm replayability. But the first playthrough is quite lengthy and so getting a full experience really does not require multiple playthroughs at all.On a lesser note, it would be nice if there were more animations for doing tasks such as gathering mushrooms, looting chests and digging up things. It would also improve the quality of life if the leveling system was longer then it currently is, as it does cap decently before the player beats the game. Same goes for if the crafting system had more variance to it now, such as acquirable recipes.All the same, genius game, the quality and length worth more then the asking price."
,Recommended,274520,29349553,Posted: 18 January,all,tehres,"An absolute masterpiece; lucky are we who are so privileged to observe its creation. 100% worth the money.If you enjoy an unfaltering atmosphere of tension, uncertainty and despair, a rich but jealously guarded story-behind-the-story which demands you work for every detail, compelling and unique gameplay and mechanics and all the best aspects of an explorative, survival horror game, then Darkwood is exactly the medicine you need to restore your faith in the notion that video games can be good.From the very beginning to the very end, Darkwood devotes every moment of the time you play to making you feel like all's wrong with the world, and you constantly at the center of it. Even the local flora are actively hostile to you, and as you make your way deeper into the woods in your attempt to escape you face only greater and greater dangers. The upgrades and new items you find come as a breath of only temporary relief as you are forced to adapt to tougher enemies, harsher environments and scarcer resources as the game goes on. And even towards the end, you'll find yourself constantly struggling to decide not what to take with you, but what you can afford to leave behind. The tension is constant, and the threats to your life are omnipresent and very persistent. Even turning your back as you walk through an open field can be devastating if you take a step in the wrong direction.The mechanics of combat and of general interaction with the rest of the world come together very nicely to create a very smooth and mostly unpunctuated experience. Combat is very skill based and fast paced, especially in the end-game areas, and the game in general requires a swift mind and swift foot to keep up with the constantly looming threat of the night. Nighttime can be either a welcome reprieve from the constant dangers you face in the day or a hellish gauntlet of relentless assault, and you'll never know which until the hounds are upon you.The story is captivating, well-told and rewarding to follow. It is hidden in the people and creatures you encounter, as well as the very environment around you, requiring much exploration and personal effort to uncover the secrets of the ruined Forest and Swamp and learn the root of the evil plauging the land. There are so many different ways to approach and complete situations that multiple playthroughs aren't just possible, but rather an absolute must, and the procedural generation is enough to provide a fresh-feeling world to play through with its own unique quirks, joys, and obstacles each time.Some claim this game is too difficult. I agree that there is difficulty, indeed, but it is just enough, and if anything it could use a little more. You will learn to be patient, thoughtful, and strong in the Forest, and all you learn will be tested in the Swamp.My profile says 240 hours or something but frankly that's an underestimate as I've followed this game since it was announced in 2013 and I played every damn version I could get my hands on until I could purchase the game for myself. I've watched it grow and evolve since weird stones did something and it's been a joy because for once I have genuine hope that Early Access has facilitated something that I am proud to say I supported and believed in from the very beginning.This is the first game I've ever played that I felt passionate enough about to write a review for. But the emptiness I felt after I played Resident Evil 4 into the ♥♥♥♥ing ground as a child was filled at last when I found this game. The disappointment I've felt with every other would-be surivival game was forgotten, and I have never looked back. If you like good survival games that you will come back to time and time again, if you like games that make you shout with joy after you manage to get inside before the nightmares behind the door tear you open, if you like games that take away from time with your friends and loved ones because ""i'll only play through one more day"", Darkwood is for you. This game earned my money, and if you give it even two hours, it will earn yours too.I give this game an x/10, where x is any real number greater than 10."
,Recommended,274520,35190386,Posted: 24 September,all,Beleth,"I've gotta say, this game packs an emotional punch I did not expect from it at first.I'm leaving the thing with the free torrent to the side, since that should not reflect on the quality of the game.Darkwood is a beautiful game.The atmospherical buildup is amazing, ambient sounds and layered environments make the relatively simple top-down perspective feel alive. You'll especially notice this in a few specific places like the giant hole in the Silent Forest, the ravine running south of the Doctor's house, and a canyon in the swamp.The gameplay is solid, combat doesn't feel slow or draggy, but takes time to get good at.The game forces you to choose how to approach a given problem. Be it a monster, preferred tactics for night defense, or moving along the plot of the game proper.Once you get the hang of if, the game becomesreallyfun to play, the whole scavenge at day defend your base at night thing isn't original, but Darkwood gives it such a good spin that that doesn't particularly matter.I love the plot elements, the feeling of being trapped in a place that's so much greater than you, the dramatic reveal if you manage to get the True ending, the sense of dread you get when you're lost, or when you won't make it back to your hideout before nighftall. The real sense of desperation that comes in when you realize you're basically standing in a dead wasteland but with more trees.I delved deep into Darkwood's lore and am a wiki editor and forum roamer, and I honestly want more.That's my complaint, there's not enough darkwood.Oh, and Acid Wizard should definetly release the official soundtrack."
