76561198055393926,Recommended,274520,33047216,Posted: 30 June,all,Halo | CaptainDonger,"Darkwood, at its core, is a game that's made to be difficult. It's a different style of difficult than some other games, but to be good at this game, it requires timing, accuracy, memorization, and serious caution. Playing, you may die many times. But every time, you grow and learn more, what not to do. There is rarely a time (except early with chompers) that you feel you were cheated when dying. A lot of the experience of the game is raw fear of the unknown. Seeing something move in a distant room through your bird's eye perception, but lacking further knowledge of what it is. It's a fear of the noises you  hear, in the creaking footsteps almost sounding outside your room's door or window. It's in the horrific thought of a person whose body morphed to become a hideous monstrosity. It's a building fear that, as you play, you become a bit hardended to. The lingering fear disappears as you become knowledgable in the environment. You'll still definitely clench for dear life onto your mouse as a chomper flies through your barricaded door, but there becomes a sort of knowing. ""Fear is a leaf off of the stem of ignorance. Once I knew what it was, it was simply a problem. Nothing to fear."" The story is really amazing too, because the game really makes you work to figure out the story. Riddles and slight pieces of information that glue into an almost imperfect web of story that is nightmarish and solemn. And you really can't have better devs. Every bug they're emailed about gets looked into, and hotfixes / updates are large and frequent.TL;DR: The game's atmosphere really feels powerful, the story is amazing, and the devs work so hard for us."
