76561197963876267,Recommended,274520,34542391,Posted: 27 August,all,Robstardum,"Dark wood is one of the more refreshingly different and clever games I have played in ages.It leaves your feeling disturbed with imagery only that of like old-school games like Sanitarium, desperate for resources like Don't Starve, and gives you the gratification of growth like a solid RPG.Generally your run of the mill horror games are pretty unthrilling: only managing to get your heart pumping through a cheap jump scare. Outliers like Amnesia are great at creating a more atmospheric-type fear but do so by capitalize on first-person mechanics to play to the player's limited visibility. Darkwood manages to somehow capture this same element of helplessness from a top-down perspective, which in my opinion, is an incredibly impressive feat given the vast amount more control you have.Through the use of multiple map layouts and randomized events (particularly during the night phases of the game) the game keeps you from being able to enter a rote mindset. Moreover, the dramatic increase in difficulty from section to section force you to improve as a player or to utilize your oh-so-precious rescourses.  Seriously, I yet to reliably kill a chomper in melee with out getting hit, bery nearly getting hit, or letting out unmannly noises.My only gripe with the game is that there is little to no material to reference when learning about the games mechanics, enemies, or the purpose of some of the items you find. I find myself constantly referencing the wiki to figure out what the random doohicky I picked up is supposed to do or what the is purpose of a random location I stumbled upon.I don't write reviews because I always feel like someone can say what I mean to say but better and with fewer words. But with this game feels like it is going to be under a lot of people's radars despite feeling like a cult classic waiting to happen. With just a smidge more awareness it will be a source of good memories (or fearful ones) on everyone's steam list. I did my part."
