76561198034979373,Recommended,274520,17532785,"Posted: 14 August, 2015",all,Bacon Abomination,"Gibbering Writhing black-mouthed chaos. Wretched foul monstrosities. The guttural wails of the half-dead and the better-off-dead. Savages made from the displacement of humanity. Beastial dogs and creatures that can only be found through the utter putrification of nature. This is what Darkwood offers. It offers something, wholly unique. It offers a world of terror that some people would ignore simply because of it being a 2D topdown survival horror game. However as a person who has been playing it as long as I have (I think the week it came out) I remember all the phases.I remember the wells at night and the mad scrambles you would make to get home. I remember scavenging through the woods and the zones trying to forage the necessary equipment to keep yourself alive. I see now, that the game has only gotten better. I remember being lucky enough to find the mirror and knowing I am nothing worse than the ghosts that surround me.When I heard it received a series of updates, I was so delighted to return to the same grim, familiar surroundings. Wolf, Chicken Lady, the poor violin kid and all the the other horrors lying in wait, with baited breath and hungry teeth, all these things made me want to come back with utter determination.I got his violin, I dragged myself a chair, I brought the Lynx back through the whole forest murdering everything in my path and contemplated murder so many times on Wolf's behalf. I met new people with nothing to say, like The Three, and fought new enemies, like the horrfiying Elk.I traversed the corn maze and I went through, carefully picking and choosing my battles until I made my way back into the same, awful woods I slithered from where I lived in the lap of squallid luxury.This is a game, where nobody is good, they are merely doing things for the sake of themselves. You can feel pity, but there is evil in everything.The cost of fresh pork? Experience a beast you can only slay by talking to a Rocket Man.That violin? You will learn what you must face to redeem the price of a sad child..That prized sow that belongs to the chicken lady? You will see the price of fresh milk in a place where nothing grows.The efforts of the Black Box? A careful eye will reveal its secret.A Red Swing. A Black Box. A White Dress.All the secrets of an apocalyptic bastion of woodland can offer you. The game is unfinished. But it's definitely worth your time. I buy and play a lot of survival games, and with the modern few I love like Frozen State, Sheltered and a few others, I offer this game a very special place in my heart.I can't review it, but if my views on the game here are any insight, buy it. Buy it cheap if you're thrifty, but buy it all the same. To me, this was like... Playing Darkwood is like planning surgery. You prepare yourself in lackluster scrubs, you enter the operating area half dazed by all the blood, and you hope to christ you don't die in the process of accomplishing your task-at-hand. It's the effort made whether you live to the end of the day, or die in a single run.Getting a gun is nice, but it doesn't kill everything in a single blast. Getting fully upgraded melee weapons is an accomplishment in and of itself but using them and surviving is what feels good.Taking on your first fight with a Chomper and winning? That's what makes the game all the worthwhile.Sure there are bugs, but I haven't a doubt in my mind they'll get fixed. Just as more mystery is made, more problems must be solved. And with any amount of effort made, I can only stand by the game being utterly, and totally satisfied for the low, low price of 15 dollars.The many ugly and unwholesome secrets of Darkwood lay ahead, awaiting your arrival. Why don't you sit and stay a spell? Don't forget your nailboard and bandages, because it's going to be a rough ride into madness friend."
