,Recommended,274520,27159145,"Posted: 24 November, 2016",all,<$>xector64,"""Challenging and Creepy""It's been a bit since I've played due to life, but this Darkwood has been a great experience for me. The crafting/survival genre of game has been running through a lot for awhile and believe me I know that can put a person off from wanting to give a go at another one. This has done it very well though, and with its own twists that make it worthwhile. The aspect of only seeing what is in the light when it is very likely trying to kill you is a challenging touch that I've come to love. My first few run throughs of this game it got me to jump and had me on the edge of my seat most of the time. It gives you chances to feel safe to only take them away with the terrors that come after you in the dark.I give it an 8/10 for what my experience has been so far.To explain my score:On the plus side, there is an interesting art style to the game, and the atmosphere created for it blends well to give it a creepy chill. The creatures are pretty challenging and horrifying creations, even the wild animals can be difficult if you aren't used to the combat system. Which is another thing, the combat system isn't too unfamiliar to those used to top down style games, but it requires a bit more strategy and reflex than some have to offer. Without spoiling too much, the crafting isn't all that unique when you look at it an overall objective way, but there are certain aspects to it that make it different and keeps the interest. I do like the ability to ""upgrade"" your character in the way implemented, so that's a plus in my book.On the down side however, as I just said the crafting is just that, crafting. What I mean by that is that it is not all that different in comparrison to other games with crafting implemented even in the idea of having to first find/build the crafting tables. The weapons aren't all too creative, even if the creatures are. Don't get me wrong I do love the touch of a more realistic feel for it, but a little fantasy wouldn't hurt in the weapon department either. I would say the bugs/unfinished story/glitches were an issue, but it's still in early access and I'd rather a long development that I can see the improvements on over time over a released version that could have been better. Which I bring up because it is my next point, the updates it has been recieving over time (yes I do keep up with at least checking the updates) is great I grow tired of games that just don't ever quite leave ""early access"" or ""beta"". I love the work they do and all, but if you wait to release a game till it's perfect it'll never really get released.What sold me on this game though...Darkwood, for what story I have seen it has been great for a fan of the creepy and horror genre. The personallity put into each character gives it a certain air of mystery to the story that makes me just need to know more. The trial and error I put into getting it ""right"" on a playthrough so I could finally make my way through to both survive as long as I can and progress through the story. The game has so much potential and they've done a great job with it thus far, and I think it will continue to do great regardless of my few gripes. The main gripe I wish they'd do something about is the combinations/treasures, which if you've played you probably know what I'm talking about.At any rate that is with as little spoil as I could manage why my rating is a solid 8/10. If you're a person who likes a challenge, that creepy feeling you get when you know somethings just out of sight, or if you just like a dark atmosphere in your games, I'd recommend you to give this game a go."
