76561197996964195,Recommended,274520,17278679,"Posted: 29 July, 2015",all,Zezima,"Let's just get one thing straight.Darkwood is a brutal game. A REALLY brutal game.If you love challanges, this game is definitely for you.If you're into zombie/scavanger type survival games this is definitely a must have then.Let's start off with with this game isDarkwood is a horror game that only goes well if you plan ahead of time.After the prologue tutorial, you play as a man with very little amounts of resources to start off with. You run around in the day time looking for wood, nails, just about anything you can fit into your invetory screen as almost all of it is important. Eventually, you'll notice that you have to go back to your hide out before night fall to drink from a well and hole up in your home. This is where it get's really interesting, and where most of your strategic planning comes into play.During the night, you'll be forced to drink from a well just outside your house, which enables you to live through the night. If you don't drink from the well in-time though, you'll start losing health untill you do. So don't travel to far out without a watch (Which you must find, or buy. You don't start off with one), or a decent sense of how long it takes to reach night time. After you drink from the well, you're most likely going to run back into your home. You can close the doors, block the hole up in your house with your furniture, and barricade the doors and windows with either panks of wood, or just more furniture. Next, you can lay traps that you may have found on your journey, arm yourself with any weapons you have crafted or found, and after alllll of that, you're going to sit, and wait for morning. And wait... and wait... oh god what are those foot steps I'm hearing? What is that growling sound? Jeezes what's with all the crows? Oh♥♥♥♥♥♥something is inside the houseWith that being said, the game has a stealth mechanic to it. Monsters have to know where you are in order to attack you. Sure they spawn outside the house at night, but they don't know your exact location yet. First off, monsters listen for your foot steps. Step to close to one that's just on the other side of the wall, and he's going to know where you are.    break into your house, and start looking for you. You can hide behind furniture, or lock yourself in another room though, maybe set up a trap at the door way.Oh, I forgot to mention, during the night, assuming you've already found out how mushrooms and leveling up work, you're going to occasionally be attacked by shadows. It won't happen every night, just every now and then. Every hide out has a generator that produces electricity for your lamps. You need gasoline (fuel) to make it work though, so don't forget to turn those things on before you go into hiding. Any source of will keep the shadows from hurting you during the night, be it flares, flashlight (Though that requires some aiming) or just lighting a fire with some gasoline.After every night, during the morning of the next day, you're going to be visited by ""The three."" These guys are going to end up being your main source of resources later on down the road.  And time for the game will freeze for the morning, meaning you have time to replace those busted barricades, and rearange your furniture for the next night.Now you can travel outside during the night. In which case you'll find more mushrooms growing about then usual (These also grow in your house) , as well as a plethora of deadly enemies. (This is not recommended at all. At any point in the game. Seriously, don't leave your hide out.)Your day time scavenging is done once again, maybe you finished a quest line, and now you're prepared to wait out the next night... Oh joy, the fog is here and the shadows are approaching! ... wait, where are the shadows? And why is the house making all kinds of shaking noises? Why is all the furniture moving?! I need those!! HOLY SH-This game will scare you, endlessly. It will kill you, repeatedly untill you figure out how to really survive. You will be paranoid about every place you go and every night you have to live through.Oh, did I mention this game features a perma death mode? If you thought this game was scarey before, try playing it without dieing once. That makes it more heart pounding then ever, as one mistake could be your last, and you'll lose every bit of progress you had made. You don't have to play perma-death, you can leave it off. When you die, you'll be able to loot your corpse, and just continue on with the days. This isn't always helpful though, if you die far off from your hide out around a heavily guarded area, you're going to have a really hard time getting your stuff back and might just have to go on without it for a while.This game is one of the most interesting survival horror games out there, and I'd recommend it to anyone looking for a good scare and action/creepy/strategically decided adventure."
