76561198176494822,Recommended,274520,34499480,Posted: 26 August,all,Shankwell,"If this game were made in the 90's, it would be the standard for all survival horror to come, like the original Fallout 1-2 and Wasteland games did for the post-apocalypic genre.  Maybe if it were the first survival horror game, the genre would be more well manicured and intelligent.  Even with all the games that have come before it, Darkwood has an exquisite sense of menace with music, tone, atmosphere and especially the relatively primitive 8-bit combat mechanics.  (You get your timing wrong and you die fast.)  Especially with your first play-through (you can easily do several), the game will have you walking backwards, nail board ready to swing at unseen noises in the forest.  Nights are deeply terrifying with a variety of threats, both imagined and real, and you can opt to patrol your base with a risk/reward of extra goodies at the expense of possibly dying with no recourse.I think my favorite aspect of the game is that despite it's 90's feel, it has a deeply sophisticated morality, both in mechanics and at a player level. On my first playthrough, I actually started to feel remorseful for what I did without even knowing I did anything bad in the first place, but I had to continue shaming myself just to stay alive.  You're allowed to make all your own choices in the game.  You have the option to kill everything in sight without any karma or alignment scale telling you if what you're doing is right or wrong on a HUD level.  There is no menu to look at that's frowning on you for helping or hindering anything.  The HUD is incredibly basic, which adds deeply to the menacing nature of the game.  Have I become a monster?  Am I still a good person?  It's impossible to tell until you've played the game for some time.I cant recommend this sophisticated, yet plain on the outside game enough.  I can't wait to see what Acid Wizard does next."
,Recommended,274520,34537149,Posted: 27 August,all,Waffles [Turbinado],"Excellent combination of survival and horror gameplay. Controls are a bit difficult to get used to at first. Nightime is always a puckering experience. Art of the NPCs is on point--although game art could perhaps use a little more polish. I would highly reccomend this game to anyone that enjoys survival, crafting, and being scared s##tless at night."
