,Recommended,274520,34626748,Posted: 30 August,all,Asteresck,"I bought this game a long time ago, and haven't played all of it, but I feel obligated to really write a review.Darkwood is one of a kind. Top-down Horror RPG. That's something. It's incredibly unique. Everything in it is something unlike anything I've ever seen before, from the vision cone, to how light is handled, and more. It's fun, too, though extremely difficult.The devs though, are probably one of the best parts of this game. They're not in it for the money. They caught people reselling Darkwood game keys at higher prices, and responded by uploading a torrent for people to play the game who don't have the money to buy it. They're good people."
,Recommended,274520,35223357,Posted: 26 September,all,Freakin' sweet!,"insanely good, almost as good as the first silent hill IMO. shame we'll never get a game like this again"
,Recommended,274520,35323783,Posted: 29 September,all,PizzaSHARK!,"The first survival horror game in a long, long time that maintains that feeling of tension even for a little while after you understand the game and how to play it.  No game can maintain tension forever after that point, but Darkwood makes it last longer than most.You wouldn't think that a top-down perspective would lend itself to horror well, but the developers clearly know what makes and breaks a survival horror game.  The combination of limited perspective, sound design, and ponderous (but never imprecise) movement and controls creates a perfect feeling of tension.  While never scary, Darkwood is often tense.While I'd say the game feels best in its permadeath form, it comes with two other modes that are somewhat forgiving (you have a limited number of lives, and you can get more by consuming a very rare item) or very forgiving (you have an unlimited number of lives.)  As far as I'm aware, none of the different modes adjust how difficult or not the actual gameplay is, only how forgiving (or not) the game is about player death.The game is separated into two chapters and tells the tale of a sort of plague in a Soviet-era Poland, or at least seems to.  While it's not on the level of something like Dark Souls or Hollow Knight, the narrative is a bit vague and the player is never quite sure if what they're seeing is real or not.Gameplay largely consists of exploring during the day, gathering supplies and fighting monsters while pursuing your ovearching goals, then seeking shelter in Hideouts to survive against the monsters until dawn.  While you're constantly going to be scavenging to improve your available weapons and even produce some simple armor, as well as repair those weapons, food and drink are never a concern for you, which is a pleasant break from one of the typically more annoying and less interesting aspects of most survival games.For anyone even vaguely interested in the survival horror genre, Darkwood is a must-have.  For everyone else, it's still absolutely worth a look, especially at its price point."
