76561198013336701,Recommended,274520,34354390,Posted: 19 August,all,TinEater,"Don't Starve crossed with Sunless Sea, but less whimsical and more pants-crappingly scary.  10/10, would pants crap again."
76561198007473066,Recommended,274520,34504191,Posted: 26 August,all,katerror,Freakesly awesome...
,Recommended,274520,34479771,Posted: 25 August,all,The Jawbone,"One of the most interesting survival horror games I've ever seen. Let's focus on that.Darkwood does not rely on the typical cliches you find in survival horror games. It doesn't even have jumpscares in its arsenal. It builds tension with its visual and audio design, and difficult gameplay. It's gone in an extremely modern pixel art direction with some relatively high res visuals which are looking remarkable even at 4k. The designs of the more ""creepy"" things are creative and immaculately animated, which definitely channels the aesthetic of Silent Hill at times.The field-of-view mechanic cannot be praised enough. It's a top-down perspective and the player character can only see objects in about a 90 degree angle in the direction he is facing. The characters attention can be focused on areas to get a better view (fading out the upper layer of trees and such) which makes for a fairly realistic, immersive feel.The combat system is simple, but feels just varied enough for this type of game. I really appreciate the use of practicality of weapon choices, as it doesn't force you to crunch damage numbers to maximize them. Got a nail board? More nails will make it do more damage, reinforcing it with metal will make it more durable.There is an element of resource management as you will never have enough materials to barricade every single window/doorframe you come across while still having enough for your equipment. A few traders exist to exchange items for reputation, a currency for buying other items. There is also a bit of procedural generation for the map across playthroughs - map layouts and locations will change, but the layouts of locations and items inside them do not.There seem to be several optional and mandatory events that involve choices for the player, that ultimately affect the storyline. In my experience, they are not weightless choices and have been slightly challenging to make at times.Overall, it's been difficult for me to notice any areas where Darkwood doesn't seem completely polished. Granted, I haven't seen all the content available, but I highly recommend it anyway."
