,Recommended,274520,11551940,"Posted: 4 August, 2014",all,Ermergewd / Spanky,"My review to DarkwoodSo what makes Darkwood different from other games that strive to unsettle you? Well, for starters, Darkwood doesn’t hinge on jump-inducing surprise-scares for its sense of tension (though it promises its fair share of these moments, anyways). Instead, Darkwood places you in a procedurally generated forest in a deeply twisted perversion of Soviet Russia. From there, the game’s dismal lighting, grotesque ambiance, and overall eerie atmosphere create the horror themselves.darkwood horror survival game gameplayIn other words, Darkwood doesn’t rely on cheap scare tactics and bursts of adrenaline to generate its terror. Darkwood’s brand of fear is the type that starts as a knot of unease in your stomach, a knot that grows tighter with each door you push slowly open, with every backwards glance and each spectral groan that floats out of the fog. Darkwood doesn’t try to scare you in the traditional Western sense – it tricks you into scaring yourself.Of course, we can’t talk about innovation in the genre without looking into the very thing that made the game stand out to me in the first place – its choice of perspective. Where most horror games seek to attach you to the protagonist by making you look through their eyes, Darkwood is the embodiment of detachment. You look down on your character from above, your line of sight limited to the swath of your flashlight beam.This means that behind you, inside buildings, anywhere that your light can’t reach, is blanketed in darkness. Nightmarish things lurk outside the light, things that you will be forced to encounter as you drift through the corrupted forest. Whether or not you survive these brushes with the frightful unknown is entirely up to you.What Else?In addition to the top-down view, Darkwood introduces some more interesting ideas. Its design has been inspired by rogue-like, adventure, and role-playing games alike, giving it a unique and nuanced feel that it seems only indie games can achieve these days.Its diverse inspirations give Darkwood a well-rounded approach to the genre, providing something enticing for every flavor of gamer. Its RPG roots have inspired the developers to include a skill-tree to the game, allowing character diversification and specialization. The looting and crafting systems are reminiscent of many survival games, from Minecraft to Fortnite, but are presented in their own uniquely gritty ways.My Rating8/10"
,Recommended,274520,35245943,Posted: 27 September,all,Spookeon ♥,"I'm gonna get this out of the way early - not a big horror game person. They dont really do much for me.This game is something special.Darkwood is one of the best mind♥♥♥♥s I've ever played. Ever. It's a psychological, top down horror game. Where you control a ♥♥♥♥ed up dude ♥♥♥♥ing up some ♥♥♥♥ed up dudes looking to ♥♥♥♥ you up, dude. Or atleast, that's the bread and butter.Behind interest scavenging elements, fun and tense combat, and a really, REALLY interesting world. This game is friggin' scary. Like, really scary. And i think a huge part of that is the atmosphere.  Between the incredible ambient music, the twisted sound effects these (probably literally) insane devs managed to make, Darkwood is really good at making you feel unsafe, and uneased, all the time. To the point that those moments of safety are more satisfying than actually killing the monsters.My thoughts..? Buy this game if you hate yourself and never want to feel safe at your computer ever again!"
