,Recommended,274520,34376446,Posted: 20 August,all,C-zom,"Darkwood is a top-down survival/horror/semi-sandbox that has a lot of game design choices borrowed from Stalker, Dark Souls, Sunless Sea and even the fundamentals of the ""survival"" niche. While you might find that recipe on the Steam page every ten games, what none of its peers have on Darkwood is atmosphere. This game bombards you with a mournful, dreadful air that never lets off the gas. Respecting both your intelligence, visual taste, and ability to pick up subtleties is what makes it such an engaging experience to people who like grit in their horror games, and nothing that is too colorful or playful or even shocking. You won't encounter a single jumpscare here.Rating: 5/5, my personal favorite game of 2017 so far. Worth it for the asking price, and any self respecting horror fan that appreciates atmosphere and substance over shock and gore should pick it up.Pros:*The combat is satisfying, the breadth of the maps is just enough to promote exploration and intrigue, the story beats are cryptic and sinister (they remind me of sunless sea's writing and style) and the day/night cycle is the best I've seen in a game besides Shadows of Chernobyl.*Atmosphere is somewhere between The Zone and Lothric. Occultism, monstrous mutants and supernatural phenomena all blend together.*In the AMA the lead developer Gustaw said he had to learn sound design from scratch. This /has/ to be a lie, because everything from the crunchy melee hits to the horrific monsters are pro jobs.*Once you get to the second and third biomes, you start to realize how insanely scary night time can be.Cons:*Early game drags, and can be a poor introduction to confused or hasty players.*Could absolutely use context, control and mechanic tutorials for the unitiated in the subgenre.*Pacing between chapters story-wise is radically different, showcasing how it took five years of inconsistent writing to finish them alpha by alpha.*Unquestionably needs some more quality of life and breadth of content. Would like to be able to build/repair furniture, have a static TV or radio of my own at night to listen to, some things to do that keep me located in the hideout even if its a farm of wormy potatos to do once a day.---In Darkwood you take control of a nameless protagonist and have to scavenge an (initially randomized) map of three biomes in order to survive. There is no hunger or thirst, just what you can build and take with you to maintain your nightly supply of generator gas to keep the monsters away, and nails/boards/weapons and ammo to survive the nights. Because while you can roam the map and encounter random hostiles with a meaty and difficult combat engine in daylight, at night time, you have to barricade your windows, slide furniture in front of gaps and just wish to survive. Rather than focusing on jumpscares, Darkwood will assail you with a dozen varieties of enemies and meta-events at night that will creep you out and also probably kill you.In day, the game feels a lot like Stalker. Named NPC's can be interacted with and have side quests and agendas of their own. Inbetween these milestone places are horrifying mutants, loose dogs and wolves, and some more supernatural enemies. Progressively each biome is pushed over to the next, much like the navigation from cordon -> garbage -> the bar etc in STALKER. While not entirely linear, it is less sandbox and more a survival/horror experience with guideposts on the story.The sound design is terrific and the minimal use of intense music and horrific noises from the dark really help to unsettle you, especially since you can only view in a 90 degree cone (whats not seen is greyed out, and you can't see enemies perfectly in a radius so they often sneak up on you.)The story is an unusual one of minimalism and style over substance, but some unnerving choices help to present the moral ambiguity of the world. I did a few things because I was told to by the only character I knew at the time, and only later found they were optional and another, ""cleaner"" path was possible. But it was too late. Much like my playthrough with Darkwood I was too brutalized, unfocused, and defeated. What happened happened.In summary if you like your survival horror games to be complete with an unnerving atmosphere of occultism and corrupted mutation, like the idea of being in ""The Zone"" again but this time with trees, always wanted a game in this niche to truly have terrifying night cycles, and have patience to respect both the slow pace and drip feed of upgrades and weapons, than this game is for you. Any self respecting horror fan who appreciates the slow burn will find in Darkwood my personal favorite game of 2017."
