,Recommended,274520,11896107,"Posted: 28 August, 2014",all,RopeDrink,"As an old-school gamer from the 80's, I've always had a soft-spot for 2D games - Especially if they cover my favourite genre, survival horror.Dark Wood may not hold your hand or throw an informative intro your way, but you learn enough to understand the situation and environment very early - And it's not a pleasant environment... Not pleasant at all...After being *rescued* by a mysterious *Doctor* during a supposed viral based epidemic (or so we're led to believe, at least in your own mind), you are thrust into a decrepid world where 'surviving' is key. Doing so requires crafting, making the choice between fight or flee, setting up a stronghold/barricade that will need to be prepared in order to fend off the creepy creatures that lurk in the night, and build your character enough that they may eventually brave deeper into the horrible world. Materials will be needed, weapons are mandatory, so there will be no bunkering down for days and hoping things go away - You will have to go out into that awful world - And there is no compass to direct you.Dark Wood is a desperate experience, from sprinting from a quest location towards your home, trying to get to safety before night rolls over the forest, to scavanging during the day only to be met by angry wildlife or vicious humanoids who are far from human.NPC's will open up quests or information when you bring them specific items, yet none of them can be considered 'normal' by any stretch. You can also opt to kill them in cold-blood and ransack their homes, if you are that way inclined. One way or the other, survival is paramount, while exploring and partaking in quests is up to you.The experience as a whole is not so much terrifying as it is permanently creepy, from corpses and destruction dotted all around the random map, to cowering in the corner of your fortified base while monsters roam outside (or even inside) your 'safehouse' while you cry and pray for morning to rise.If you're a fan of the 2D style and enjoy crafting/barricade based survival horror, with a dirty creepy world to explore and the simple fact that running is a VERY valid option over fighting for your life, then you'll love Dark Wood.I'll be watching the growth of this game with interest and can't wait to see what else it adds into the mix."
