,Not Recommended,274520,17703035,"Posted: 24 August, 2015",all,Buzzo,"I really want to like this game, but try as I may, I just cannot.Bought it way back in like 2015 when it was still in Alpha. Regardless of how much I try to play it, I just don't seem to like it unfortunately. ""Unforgiving"" is a word that's used a bit too literally in this game. It's not difficult to the point of wanting to retry things, it's difficult to the point of not wanting to attempt to play it at all (and before anyone says ""git gud"" — I'm a big fan of hard games, just not when they end up boring me), even on normal. The atmosphere is fantastic, but the pacing is so ♥♥♥♥ing slow that I can't play it for more than a couple minutes before I want to stop. Calling it a survival game but taking out the things that one needs to survive (food, water) and replacing them with just this system of using mushrooms that do not respawn is just an odd design choice to me, but some others may like it. It's survival in the sense of having to wait through a 10 minute night cycle by standing really close to an oven (why? I don't know.). Sure, the sound is fantastic as well, to the point where you don't dare venture outside during the night, and even moving in your own house is scary... but what does that accomplish? Night cycles don't seem to really DO anything. You hide in a corner and wait for the sun to come up, then flounce around a very ""same-y"" map for a while, and repeat. I don't get the fun aspect.Regardless of how I feel about Darkwood, the developers are very open and kind to their customers, and constantly try to fix the game to please their fanbase, even when it meant putting in way more work than they were anticipating. I applaud that attitude and work ethic, and so I'll simply chock this game up to ""not my style."" I may not like it personally, but AcidWizard is a shining example of how a dev team SHOULD handle EA, the likes of which I've only seen by Hinterland behind The Long Dark."
