,Not Recommended,274520,11464842,"Posted: 29 July, 2014",all,Wistfane,"Darkwood is a top down survival game that plays like an old school GTA or Hotline Miami ableit much slower. You are a greasy hobo living in a shack and your goal is to navigate a randomly generated verdant plot of land and eventually escape it.The games prologue is a short tutorial but frankly it doesnt do a good job of preparing you for the game. Many mechanics such as cooking, leveling up and using perks is not explained.Visually the game is simple and draws alot of inspiration from Slender and Silent Hill for tis spooky atmosphear which it pulls off pretty well.The sound minimal however it effectively punctuates the highs and lows of the game. The sound effect are really well done and go a long way to enhance the atmosphere.As nice as it all sound the game is still an alpha and after playing for 11 hours it still needs a long way to go before being anywhere close to enjoyable.While the ideas are solid the game suffers from quite a few game game breaking bugs. Crashes and black screens are common and so are various glitches which you should familirise yourself with if you intent of getting anywhere in this game.The odds are stacked heavily against you and dying is a common and costly occurence. You are defeceless when unarmed and unless you restarded the game a few times it will a be a while before you get your first weapon.  Sadly even then your chances of remaining unscathed are pretty slim. Most enemies have either a longer reach a lunge or plain old stunlock though a flurry or blows so getting to know your enemies is important and in most cases you cant take on more than one baddy at a time.Your weapons seem to be made of styrophoam since most of them break after every fight and rapairs or resupplies are very costly. Despite te starting vendor selling ammo for various firearms I have yet to see most of them. I have only used the double barrel shotty and the pellet gun both of which were jaringly inferior to the axe.If you are getting the jist that this game is hard you have heard nothing yet. The game uses a day and night cycle ( aprox 15/9 irl min) During the days you forrage and complete quests and during the night you fend off baddies enmasse.Problem is if you play the game as intended you wont last more than 2 days so you have resort to an exploit of hiding in a corner under total darkness in oder to skip the nighttime assaults.Exploring during the day is equaly agonising because of your characters speed and stamina you barely have enough time to explore one location before heading back to your shack. Sprinting all the time is also unadvisable for the woods are densely populated by bear traps and poisonus fungi ( which you need ot harvest to level up) and if you want to venture deeper into the woods you are required to have a light source of a kind. Issue is some of the most uggliest baddies and lot interesting quest set pieces are located in the deeper woods. This leaves you spirinting though the woods blind triping over traps or takign and slow and takign a beating from a pack of hungry mosnters.All in all after 11 hours the end is nowhere near in sight and I barely have any progress on my first quest. Before commiting yourself finnacialyl to this game the needsto be a lot of bug fixing and rebalancing done. I also urge the devs to do away with the random world generation since it add nothing to the game but frustration.Verdict: wait for it to get better. Hopefully this will grow into a nice gem"
