76561198029260973,Recommended,274520,11940484,"Posted: 31 August, 2014",all,DreadShot1337,This game is probably one of the most challenging games of this era. The game combines a element of fear and survival. To make things harder there is a perma-death option.
76561197992318249,Recommended,274520,11943326,"Posted: 31 August, 2014",all,Edgelord Dankmeme,"Despite being early access, this game already has a lot going for it. The oppressive atmosphere really helps to immerse players into the game, while the overall difficulty really cements the fact that here in the forest the player is not the most dangerous thing lurking in the darkness. The gameplay is fairly simple at the moment; from a top-down view the player walks around the game world, their line of site represented by a visual cone, when the character is not facing something like, say, a searchable pile of rubble or a wandering enemy or NPC, they disappear from the game map, though you can still hear them. This is used to quite terrifying effect if your power goes out and a monster breaks into your home, as your field of view shrinks tremendously, or when you need to craft a weapon or use something from your inventory, as your field of vision disappears while your character has to rummage around inside his pack. Melee combat is fairly simple but rewarding, and good timing is key to surviving any unavoidable confrontation. I've seen gameplay of firearms, but have yet to personally acquire one myself.The story, at this point, isn't all that clear to me. The bare bones of it is that the player character is stranded within a forest of the Soviet Block, apparently after some form of horrific mind and body altering plague outbreak, however, this is certainly not just another generic ""and then zombies"" story. The creatures and characters you will meet have been transformed or changed in very strange and terrifying ways. The current goal of the player seems to be to find their way out of the forest, a task that will take them quite some time as they must survive multiple nights, hidden in their homes as they are set upon by monstrosities from God knows where.The game, being in early Alpha, does have its issues though.As stated before, the game is quite difficult. Extremely so, to be honest. Chances are very high that, like myself, players will not find any remotely decent melee weapons for the first few nights at best, and will be forced to either run around their home all evening to flee from any intruding monsters or waste precious limited nails and wood boards used to barricade doors and windows or repair doors or windows to make what is essentially the crappiest weapon you can have; board with nails. This is accentuated by the fact that the map is randomly generated, with locations being spread out across different areas each time. Only once have I ever found an Axe within the first two nights, and that was pure luck.Currently there is no difficulty option, and so players will constantly come face to face with extremely powerful and fast monsters. You can outrun most of them, but many can easily keep pace with the player, who will eventually run out of stamina when sprinting. When the player dies, they lose the remainder of the current day they were on, unless playing in Permadeath, as well as any collected items such as Mushrooms, while also taking large damage to any item with a durability meter, such as weapons, gas cans, or flashlights and lanterns. The game essentially punishes players for dying multiple times over, as the only way to repair melee weapons, for instance, is to find Repair Kits, which so far have been few and far between at best, which more or less forces one to make the decision of whether it's even worth it to bring a weapon or durability item with them outside of Permadeath because should they die it loses something near half of its durability, and every single bit is precious in this game where virtually everything you cannot speak to is trying to eat your face.Hopefully in a future update, the durability of items will either be raised or the health of enemy monsters will be lowered, or some form of difficulty option will be implemented. I truly enjoy this game, but having all of my items breaking because I'm trying to explore to find objects to PREVENT myself from having my items breaking gets quite tiresome. Finding an Axe and Repair Kit only to have your house randomly besieged by a bird-headed beast and something that resembles a Schism from Silent Hill: Homecoming on the second night, dying, and then having to use that one precious Repair Kit just to ensure I can fix up my axe and try to not die the next night is not what I'd call fun, but tedious.The game could definitely benefit from some more crafting options, such as  more traps. So far the only traps I'm aware of are Bear traps, which the player finds strewn about in the forest or in crates and such, or smashing some bottles to make broken glass. I'm surprised there's no option for, say, using some nails and a board to create a nail strip to put on window sills or something to that effect. Perhaps some wooden stakes the player could place outside of doors or windows to damage enemies that walk through them.  These do not need to do ludicrous amounts of damage, I just thought it would be a nice touch, seeing as how it's odd your character only seems to have the intelligence of nailing boards to door frames and windows, and not building much of anything else with them. They could even make the costs for such craftable things rather high, such as requiring 15 nails for one nail strip, or 10 boards for a single set of wooden stakes. Seeing as how these resources are fairly limited anyway, I don't see much issue in alloowing more options for people to use them on.In the game, you can actually smash down doors and windows if, say, they are barricaded or locked. This offers another method of getting into locations should you lack a key or lockpick. However windows, and even when unbarricaded, doors have a ludicrous amount of durability. I'm not sure what those Soviets made their bedroom doors out of, perhaps reinforced concrete? Most weaponry, besides an Axe, breaks before a door or barricaded window is even at a third of its overall durability. These are, for all intents and purposes, old wooden doors with some old wooden boards nailed behind them. Why then does it take roughly a third of an axe's durability to chop one down, even when it's simply locked?There's no way to attack without a melee weapon. The player cannot swing a punch or anything of the sort. While this does make the game more challenging, I also find it incredibly strange when facing another human enemy or wild dog that we cannot at least throw some exceptionally weak punches to fend them off. In most cases this would be suicide anyway, as once again, the enemies can take a fairly ridiculous amount of punishment while also dealing well over the damage the player deals in many cases, but it would still be nice to even have the option of being able to pathetically defend ourselves. I'm fairly certain if a naked man cornered me inside my home and began hurling rocks at me, I would at least try and defend myself, not continually run around the room.Perks at this point in time are somewhat pointless, unless you can survive for exceptionally long periods of time you will simply die and lose the perks you just wasted some of the limited number of mushrooms you've gathered on. I've simply taken to storing the mushrooms in hopes of selling them later. Once again, a difficulty where the player could actually keep the perks to see the actual fruits of their labors would be nice.Every night at the start of the night cycle, the player must drink from the well outside their home, or else die from...whatever sort of plague or disease is currently ravaging their body. This is an interesting feature, however it requires the player to remain soleley at their beginning house where the well is located. There are a number of other ""friendly"" NPCs around the map whom are most likely suffering from the same ill-effects as the player character, and yet you are the only one with a well outside of your home. It'd be cool to be able to set up shop at other homes with wells."
