,Recommended,274520,13772324,"Posted: 1 January, 2015",all,Jaffers,"Played this for about 10 or more hours before the alpha 2.1 update. Really thouroughly enjoyed it, although as a survival horror where punishment is so severe, its slow going. Lack of story in these parts can end up making it a chore just to play. As well as complete save wipes with every early access update and game mechenics changing to the point where I have to relearn how to play every time, I am going to wait until the game is fully released and polished before I put many valueble hours into playing it from start to finish. Aside from that I quite like the survival aspects, the environmental interaction and the fact that you have to experiment with things. Be prepared for trial and error and a massive learning curve, although this is where all the fun is. When you do progress or things go right, it feels really good as a change from the brutal world. Unique and unlike most top down or horror genres. Definitely worth a play and should be on your wishlist at the very least.TL;DRPros:-Unique-Rewarding gameplay in contrast to brutal punishment-So far has a very good story line, explained through the world and actions as well as NPC dialogue-Interesting-CRAFTING!-BASES!-Survival horror is very well doneCons:-Slow game play can lead to slow story progression and thus it can become dry-Death really sucks-Early access updates wipe your save-Sometimes cluncky controlsWorth a buy 7.5/10"
,Recommended,274520,13815356,"Posted: 3 January, 2015",all,IvyWinter,"I've been playing Darkwood for a couple of days now and I have to say, as a survival horror fan, this game is refreshing. It is DIFFICULT,so don't go into it thinking it'll ease you into anything. It won't. You don't get a lot of supplies, you have limited time to wander from your safehouse to find new locations and your map is elementary at best. You'll often be completely lost wandering around the woods, and that's part of what makes the game so scary, especially when the sun is going down and you can't remember where your safehouse is.The other night, I sat in the dark with my one light on as my generator was running, and heard dogs outside the house. Suddenly, the dogs started yelping. something was KILLING them. My lights went out, i turned on my torch, and this shambling dude comes up to me with a stick, moaning. I got a couple of good hits on him and he ran, while shadows suddenly surrounded me in my lack of light....and then bam. Morning.Seriously one of the most tense games I've played. I can't wait to see how it turns out when it is out of alpha and complete!"
,Recommended,274520,13738013,"Posted: 31 December, 2014",all,mordaunt,"Tl;DR: Dark. Scary. Unforgiving. Awesome.I've played a few hours when Alpha 2.0 was out. This game has really surprised me, in a good sense. It looks really promising in its current state.It's really hard, you are never spoonfed and learn by mistakes (most of them will kill you). Your highest priority is survival: gathering resources, crafting items and weapons to save you from the horrors of the night in the woods. Trust me, there's nothing like hiding in a corner of your house, in the dark, hearingsomethingkilling all the weaker creatures outside then bashing into your barricaded doors, moaning and growling.The characters are quite memorable. Even with few dialogue lines they have, I felt that no one in the woods should be trusted. They're all hiding something. The protagonist is just as strange and sick, having to quench his deadly thirst from the well every night.The graphics are lovely. Nothing too fancy, but almost every location looks like it was carefully crafted. I got that feel of presence while being in the woods. Oh, and the world is randomly generated, so every new playthrough means a new scheme of your survival."
