,Recommended,274520,34558942,Posted: 28 August,all,Kias,"I have been eyeing this game for awhile but didn't want to play another early access title. I was actually a bit shocked to see it released and jumped right in with what little free time I have these days (#dadlife) to see if it would scratch that survival, exploration itch I am always looking for.It did, with a healthy dose of horror, immersion, and a nice set of gameplay mechanics to boot.The narrative is very much in the dark souls fashion where you can discover as much or as little as you like as you play through the game. Item scarcity is balanced well enough that the game rewards convservation but won't punish you for using your goodies. Exploration is thematically satisfying and mechanically rewarding, with those who are willing to look in every cranny often gaining access to equipment, upgrades, and items earlier than they may normally be available. Extra bonuses await the puzzle solving sorts if you want to figure out the combinations to the dozens of optional stashes scattered throughout the game.The combat and survival balance felt solid in my one normal game run. Even when I was sporting a shotgun and a stack of shells, I never felt fully safe in the woods and the variety of night time encounters kept me on my toes no matter how well set up I made my hideout. It has a kind of difficulty that stays manageable so long as you are taking your time, but all it takes is a few panicked/rushed/complacent moments and things can go wrong quick. Bear traps will be your best friend and your worst enemy.Also, fun fact: The most terrifying thing a monster can do is knock politely and persistently on your front door. I'm not home, please go away."
