,Recommended,274520,32893921,Posted: 27 June,all,Quakeguy,"Darkwood is the sort of video game that is incomparable to any other. This game is not only a labor of deep love, but it is so carefully crafted and exotic that attempting to compare it to any other released title does neither any justice. This is a top-down game that will have your pants filling from the♥♥♥♥♥downwards with a genuine crafted horror. This is Slavic horror at its absolute finest- a young Polish group breaking all sorts of molds due in part to them being naive and enthusiastic. ""Hotline Miami meets Blair Witch"" is something I have seen said several times about this game- it's simply not a proper comparison. This game is more psychologically distorted than Hotline Miami. The tension built, released, and built up again far exceeds the layered pacing of The Blair Witch.In terms of Combat, it is simple in its execution and varied in its approach. Melee, ranged, traps, and environmental usage all take factor. Its simplicity is a boon, and allows for very creative aggression from the player and nail biting defenses in the games evenings. The better weapons, the more you feel the weight of their impact on the enemies. The more accurate you become with the very rare guns that exist, the more satisfying they feel to use. Scarcity of ammunition and the requirement to repair weaponry add to a constant tension of knowing when to err on the side of caution.In terms of sound production, design, and usage, I cannot think of an indie game which has done it better. The utilization of sound effects in this game is absolutely top notch. I cannot sing the praises of this enough- everything from radio static, to enemy noise, to the differing weight in footprints allowing veteran players to know precisely what is lurking and stalking them adds to the atmosphere in the best of ways.Every other scene or building you will explore in Darkwood contains plot, lore, character development- all of which feed into an over-arching narrative that many players will not experience in a first playthrough, or second. For those looking for a story-driven horror game, Darkwood will offer you this in spades. There is no narrator telling you how to interpret the clues you find. As you play more, as you look back on your in-game journal and review information, cross-reference baubles with the locations they were found in, you will discover more and more stories in Darkwood than you thought existed. Each of them unlocks yet another piece to a puzzle you genuinely wish to solve.All of this is done without sacrificing the flow of the game. You can choose to think hard about what you find and piece it together, or simply marvel at the brains that would conjur such macabre machinations and continue just trying to escape Darkwood.This game is for a particular audience: for those who remember what it was like to be scared by video games in the 1990's and early 2000's, with all the lights off in your room and the television RCA/SD cables providing a warm comforting glow to the scares they were producing to you. Personally, I am a rather jaded, pessimistic, and cynical gamer these days. There hasn't been a game released in the last 5 years on the PC which has genuinely horrified me like Darkwood has. I am very difficult to manipulate into falling for the 'atmosphere' that developers in AAA companies desperately try and create. Darkwood is like the 'PT' demo outstretched for 15-20 hours of gameplay on your first playthrough- and trust me, you will replay it again."
