,Recommended,274520,12711491,"Posted: 31 October, 2014",all,Leonard McCoy,"Darkwood is thick with atmosphere, tension, story—top-down survival horror at its very best. The entire package on offer is entirely enchanting and unique. An immensely satisfying, suspenseful journey not for the fainthearted!Darkwood has come a long way since its Early Access release in 2014 which was already a surprisingly polished showing. Over the span of three years additional development time has allowed the game to grow considerably in terms of contents. Several key gameplay components (such as progress from area to area) have also been completely revamped for the better. It's a complete package now that still keeps me on the edge of my seat even after 40-plus hours of playing.Darkwood's gameplay is governed by two phases: day and night. Daylight provides relative safety from raving creatures and it allows you to explore this dark fantastical world filled with unique and bizarre characters. Scavenge for materials, repair the hideout, craft and discover new tools and ultimately find a way out of the dark woods by unveiling many of its dark and mysterious secrets.At night you are at your most vulnerable. Barricade your hideout, repair doors and windows, upgrade the workbench to craft better stuff and prepare defend from any uninvited guest or ravenous creature. You should probably even drag some furniture in front of every door, equip a weapon, and cower in fear in one of the corners of the room. And once the light goes out because your generator is low on fuel or something, you might be in real trouble...In short, Darkwood is a real indie gem—it's difficult to fully convey how immensely satisfying and suspenseful the journey is in Darkwood. It's also one of those games where cranking up the gamma slider does nothing but rob you of that heart-rendering experience the game is trying to envelope you in. It's best played on nightmare difficulty (the way it was meant to be played) and in a darkened room with headphones on."
